      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "# 1. Why Arrays?\n",
        "---\n",
        "## 1.1 The issue with lists\n",
        "\n",
        "Typically in Data Science, you'll often want to carry out operations over entire collections of values, and you want to do this fast.\n",
        "\n",
        "With lists, this is a problem!"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "0fdeb9f8-e841-4638-8a81-bcd14db18ffd",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "0fdeb9f8-e841-4638-8a81-bcd14db18ffd"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "## Example - BMI\n",
        "# RUN-TOGETHER\n",
        "\n",
        "# Suppose we have height and weight data for a collection of people\n",
        "# Our goal is to calculate BMI for each person\n",
        "# We can calculate BMI as weight/height^2\n",
        "\n",
        "height = [1.73, 1.68, 1.71, 1.89, 1.79]\n",
        "weight = [65.4, 59.2, 63.6, 88.4, 68.7]\n",
        "\n",
        "bmi = weight/height**2\n",
        "\n",
        "# This doesn't work. What's the issue?"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "31c898ca",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "31c898ca"
      },
      "source": [
        " For a **list**, `**` and `/` are not defined element-by-element; there is no way to say \"divide each weight by each height squared\" without a loop. We want something that just does the math. That is NumPy."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "Z0CgAsSr6Jyv",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Z0CgAsSr6Jyv"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 1.2 NumPy to the Rescue!\n",
        "\n",
        " ** Note, you may need to install numpy on your own system prior to using the package **\n",
        "\n",
        "NumPy provides an alternative to lists: arrays\n",
        "- Similar to lists, but allow for calculations across the array\n",
        "- Fast!\n",
        "\n",
        "**Definition.** A NumPy *array* (`ndarray`) is an ordered collection of values, like a list, but with two superpowers: (1) math happens **element-wise** across the whole array, and (2) it is fast (the looping runs in compiled C, not Python).\n",
        "\n",
        "One rule: NumPy arrays can contain only **one** type of data.\n",
        "\n",
        "- If you create a \"mixed\" array, Python will convert the data to a more general type (like `str`)\n",
        "- NumPy arrays are another type of object (like `str`, `float`, and `list`)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "25112e93-eed4-494a-a326-65b1bfb0ba70",
      "metadata": {
        "collapsed": true,
        "id": "25112e93-eed4-494a-a326-65b1bfb0ba70"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "## Example - BMI\n",
        "# RUN-TOGETHER\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "height_m = np.array([1.73, 1.72, 1.61, 1.89, 1.79])\n",
        "weight_kg = np.array([65.4, 59.2, 63.6, 88.4, 68.7])\n",
        "\n",
        "bmi = weight_kg/height_m**2\n",
        "print(bmi)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Calculations were performed element-wise\n",
        "print(65.4/1.73**2)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "c16540b2",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "c16540b2"
      },
      "source": [
        "Methods are associated with arrays, and may behave differently than other methods with the same name\n",
        "\n",
        "### Activity 1: Predict, then run.\n",
        "Lists and arrays react to `+` completely differently. Predict each result before running.\n",
        "\n",
        "- `[1, 2, 3] + [1, 2, 3]`  is going to output _____\n",
        "- `np.array([1,2,3]) + np.array([1,2,3])` is going to output _____"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "953d096f-c494-4e5a-b333-412408ffebc3",
      "metadata": {
        "collapsed": true,
        "id": "953d096f-c494-4e5a-b333-412408ffebc3"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# RUN-TOGETHER\n",
        "python_list = [1,2,3]   #S tandard list\n",
        "numpy_array = np.array([1,2,3])   # Standard array\n",
        "\n",
        "print(python_list + python_list)\n",
        "print(numpy_array + numpy_array)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(python_list[1])\n",
        "print(numpy_array[1])"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "c52f98f1",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "c52f98f1"
      },
      "source": [
        "### 1.3 The homogeneity rule\n",
        "\n",
        "Because an array holds one type, mixing types forces a promotion to a common type. This is worth seeing on purpose so it never surprises you."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "d48986cc",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "d48986cc"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "## Example\n",
        "# FILL-IN-LIVE together: predict the type, then run. bool + int -> ?\n",
        "mixed1 = np.array([True, 1, 2])\n",
        "print(mixed1, '->', mixed1.dtype)\n",
        "\n",
        "mixed2 = np.array([1, 2, 'go']) # int + str\n",
        "print(mixed2, '->', mixed2.dtype)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "a05c5b85",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "a05c5b85"
      },
      "source": [
        "### 1.4 Broadcasting: array meets scalar\n",
        "\n",
        "*Broadcasting* is how NumPy applies an operation between an array and a single value: the single value (called a scalar) is applied to every element."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "fadee79e",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "fadee79e"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
