    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "ce77da8e",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "ce77da8e"
      },
      "source": [
        "In data science, we commonly want our data arranged in a different way than what we see in `players`. We prefer that each row is an observational unit (i.e. player) and each column is a feature (i.e height, weight).\n",
        "\n",
        "We will need to swap rows and the columns so that the height, weight rows become height, weight columns. This can easily be done by using the transpose attibute."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "1b273ce5",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "1b273ce5"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "print('original:\\n', players) # \\n forces a line break\n",
        "players_dat = players.T\n",
        "print('transposed:\\n', players_dat)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "d4fec2d1",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "d4fec2d1"
      },
      "source": [
        "### 2.1 Indexing and slicing of 2D arrays\n",
        "\n",
        "> array_name[row, column] produces the element in location (row, column)\n",
        "\n",
        "Note, in Python:\n",
        "- indexing starts a 0\n",
        "    - `array_name[0,0]` is the element in first row and first column.\n",
        "    - `array_name[-1,-1]` is the last element (negative counts from the end).\n",
        "- `:` produces all values\n",
        "- `array_name[row]` or `array_name[row, :]`produces the single row indexed by `row`\n",
        "- `array_name[:, column]` produces the single column indexed by `column`\n",
        "\n",
        "We can slice vales from rows, from columns, or both using the notation `start:stop`\n",
        "- Remember: the slice is from `start`, up to but **not including** `stop`.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "ab7b8232",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "ab7b8232"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "print(players_dat)\n",
        "\n",
        "# data for first player\n",
        "print('player 0:', players_dat[0])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Access the element in the third row and first column\n",
        "print(players_dat[2,0]) # Remember 0 indexing!\n",
        "print(players_dat[2][0]) # also works!\n",
        "\n",
        "# Access the elements for the forth and fifth person\n",
        "# Think first:\n",
        "# start = 3: fouth person is in row 3 because index starts at 0\n",
        "# end = 5: need one more than where we want to stop\n",
        "print('fourth and fifth:\\n', players_dat[3:5,:])\n",
        "\n",
        "# boolean mask heights < 70\n",
        "# Think first:\n",
        "# first column of heights: players_dat[:,0]\n",
        "# boolean mask: players_dat[:,0] < 70  -> False False ....\n",
        "print('height < 70:\\n', players_dat[players_dat[:,0] < 70, :] )"
      ]
