      "source": [
        "### 2.2 The `axis` arguement\n",
        "\n",
        "** Definition.** For a 2D array, the input to a method of `axis=0` collapses *down the rows* (one answer per column) when appling the method, while `axis=1` collapses *across the columns* (one answer per row).\n",
        "\n",
        "For example, if we have columns of quantatative features and we want to take the mean of each feature, we would use: `array.mean(axis = 0)`"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "99e95b47",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "99e95b47"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "print(players_dat)\n",
        "print('mean values:\\n', players_dat.mean(axis = 0))\n",
        "\n",
        "# What does this code do?\n",
        "#print('mean values:\\n', players_dat.mean(axis = 1))"
      ]
